Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp} for the rice.

Meanwhile, heat a medium #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

When hot, add the @lamb mince{200%g} and use a #spoon{} to break up the mince. Fry,
stirring occasionally, until browned all over, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> TIP: Drain away any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw mince.

When the water for the rice is boiling, add the @basmati rice{150%g} and cook for
~{12%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve{}, pop back in the pan, cover with a #lid{} and leave to the
side until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @cucumber{1/2} lengthways, scoop out the seeds and discard them. Chop
into small pieces and pop into a #medium bowl{}.

Pick the @mint{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Once the lamb has browned add the red onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until
softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the garlic, @harissa paste{50%g}, @chermoula spice mix{1} and
@tomato puree{30%g} and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add the @water{100%ml} and @chicken stock paste{10%g} and stir together.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, bring to the boil and cook for
~{2-3%minutes} until slightly thickened and the lamb is cooked through.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

In a medium bowl mix the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75%g}, chopped cucumber and
half of the mint.

Stir well to combine. This is your tzatziki. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Once the sauce has thickened and the rice is cooked, add the rice to the pan and
mix well to combine.

Share the lamb and rice between your bowls.

Spoon the tzatziki on top and sprinkle over the remaining mint. Enjoy.